      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":450,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 5-minute brisk walk to ease into movement. Focus on relaxed breathing and loose shoulders.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a comfortable, conversational pace. You should be able to speak in full sentences. If you feel breathless, slow down — there is no pace too slow here.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease back to a walk for the final 5 minutes. Let your heart rate come down naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 5-minute brisk walk. Add a few gentle leg swings and ankle circles before you start running.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes after finishing. Follow with light stretching of calves, quads, and hip flexors — hold each for 20–30 seconds.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundational aerobic run for the week. At this stage of your training, easy runs are doing the most important work — building your aerobic engine, strengthening connective tissue, and teaching your body to run efficiently. The 7:00–8:00/km pace range is your sweet spot: slow enough to recover, fast enough to build fitness. If 4 km feels like a lot right now, it's completely fine to run 3 km and walk the rest. Consistency over the coming weeks matters far more than any single session.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":390,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"5-minute brisk walk to warm up. Focus on relaxed posture and easy breathing.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at your easy conversational pace. Keep effort light — this is not a hard day.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":6,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"4 x 20-second gentle accelerations (strides). Not sprinting — think of gradually picking up your cadence and running tall for 20 seconds, then walking 40 seconds between each. These teach your legs to move a little faster without taxing your aerobic system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk back to your starting point or home. Let everything settle.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5-minute walk, then ease into your easy run pace. No need for extra drills today — the strides later in the session serve as neuromuscular activation.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 4 minutes. Stretch calves, hamstrings, and hip flexors gently. These strides can leave your legs feeling pleasantly activated — that's normal and good.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This midweek session has a small but meaningful addition: four short strides toward the end of your easy run. Strides are brief accelerations — not sprints — that gently introduce your legs to faster turnover. The physiological benefit is neuromuscular: you're teaching your muscles and nervous system to coordinate at a slightly higher speed, which will translate directly to your 5K pace on race day. They're short enough (20 seconds each) that they don't add meaningful fatigue. Think of them as a conversation with your legs about what's coming in the weeks ahead.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Easy Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":465,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":465,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Begin with a 5-minute walk. Take your time — long run days benefit from a gentle start.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":465,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at the easier end of your easy pace range — closer to 8:00/km than 7:00/km. The goal today is time on feet, not speed. If you need to walk for 1–2 minutes at any point, that is completely fine and still counts as productive training.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 5 minutes. This is non-negotiable on long run day — your body needs this transition.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with a 5-minute walk. Consider doing a few gentle hip circles and leg swings before you begin running. Hydrate before you head out.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes minimum. Today's cooldown is especially important — follow with a full-body stretch focusing on calves, quads, hamstrings, glutes, and hip flexors. Consider a short foam roll if you have one.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your long run day, and it's the cornerstone of your 5K preparation. This might feel counterintuitive — why does a 5K runner need a long run? The answer is aerobic infrastructure. Your long run builds the mitochondrial density, capillary networks, and fat-burning efficiency that underpin everything else. At 6 km this week (up from your current 5 km long run), we're making a modest but meaningful step forward. The pace should feel genuinely easy — if you're working hard, you're going too fast. A good rule of thumb: you should be able to hold a conversation the entire time. If you can't, slow down. There is no pace too slow on long run day.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
